Rating: 4
I've made this recipe every St. Patty's Day for the past five years and it is as good as they say-OUTSTANDING! I've made just a few modifications over the years, sometimes cooking just for my family, at other times for more than 30 people. Here are my suggestions: After adding the corned beef to the pot add 2 bottles of Guiness Stout and then add the water. The recipe says to add water to cover but increase the amount of liquid because you're going to want to add a few pounds of small red potatoes later and you'll need the additional liquid. Don't bring the water to a boil (if you can help it) but only to a simmer. After the water begins to simmer adjust the heat lower periodically-every 5-10 minutes or so until you've got it simmering on low. Skim the top after one hour of simmering and then add the pickling spices. Add a couple of cans of chicken broth mid way through cooking. After washing the potatoes I peel them only partially-making a stripe around the midsection. Add the potatoes during the last hour of cooking. I also use 2 heads of cabbage (during the last 20 minutes) and a small bag of peeled mini carrots-sometimes more if I'm cooking for a lot of people. Serve the cabbage with red wine vinegar. If making more than two briskets do one with the bourbon glaze. Serve the other brisket with a quality stone ground mustard. (Don't be afraid to splurge for the expensive stuff-it's worth it!) Make the horseradish sauce and serve it on the side as well-it's great with the potatoes! Happy St. Patrick's Day!

