Rating: 4
About the question of substituting another cut of meat: The corned beef is pink because it is pickled in sodium nitrite/nitrate. An untreated roast will not produce the same result in this recipe . I have tried several times to make my own corned beef and have googled extensively in search of the right recipe. I recommend Joan Nathan's recipe from her wonderful and essential cookbook, "Jewish Cooking In America". You can find nitrite in the salt section of most supermarkets, for example, Morton's "tender quick" If you want to leave out the saltpeter, as Joan calls it, your beef will be gray rather than pink, and the texture will not be quite the same. 1 4-pound brisket of beef 1/4 cup large-grained kosher salt 1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper 2 teaspoons ground ginger 1/2 teaspoon ground cloves 2 bay leaves, crumbled 1 tablespoon brown sugar 1/8 teaspoon nutmeg 1/8 teaspoon paprika 3 cloves garlic, minced 1 tablespoon saltpeter (optional) 1/2 cup warm water Wash and remove most of the fat from the brisket. Mix all the spices and the garlic and rub well into the brisket. Dissolve the saltpeter in the warm water and pour over the meat. Place in a large, non-metal container. Weight the meat down with a stone or brick and cover it with plastic wrap or aluminum foil. (You can also place the ingredients in a plastic bag and weight it down.) Refrigerate for 10 days to 2 weeks. Turn the meat every 2 to 3 days. Place the meat in a large pot of cold water. Bring to a boil and throw away the water. Repeat 3 times. Cover with cold again, bring to a boil, and cook over low heat, covered, for about 2 hours or until tender. Cool slice thin, and place on a platter.

