Rating: 4
For those using a smaller cut of meat, stick to the 1 hour per pound rule. Last night, 12 of my friends (ages 7 to 64) gave this recipe 4 forks and said it was the best corned beef they ever had. I actually never saw so many people really enjoying this dish! I cooked up 15 lbs of the stuff (4 point cuts aprx 3.5 lbs each, 3 cabbages, 4 lbs of carrots 3 large turnip and 5 lbs of potatos). Excellent! The key is to use the 1 hour per pound formula and simmer (never boil!). I used my huge counter top roaster, boiled water separately, poured on top of the meat and brought it to a simmer for 3 1/2 hours adjusting temp between 350-400 degrees so it NEVER boiled. Not only did I use the spices included with the meat, but added a TBL of peppercorns, a sprinkle of hot pepper flakes, 2 bay leaves, 1 tsp. whole allspice, and 10 or so cloves. Added a can of Guiness an hour into it. I took the meat out before my guests arrived as they came in 2 shifts, 2 hours apart. I made my version of glaze simmering til it turned to a thick syrup...1 jar of apricot preserves, a healthy squeeze of wasabi sauce and dijon mustard and bourbon. When the first group arrived, I added potatos to the pot of broth for 15 mins ahead then the turnip & carrots for 15 more before adding the cabbage for 20. The meat was glazed and put into a 400 degree oven while the veggies continued to cook for 15-20 mins and let it stand for 10 before slicing. The meat was firm but very tender and the veggies perfect in each of there own! Looks like St PAtty's day is at our house from now on!

