This is one of my favorites! I discard the spices that come with the brisket and add about 10 peppercorns, a couple of whole cloves, 2 bay leaves and a clove of garlic, all wrapped in cheesecloth so as not lose them. I agree with the other readers - the combo of water and beer does make a difference, although it is fine with just water, too.

Rating: 3
Funny enough, corned beef and cabbage isn't actually very common in Ireland! It's more of an Irish-American dish. In Ireland you're more likely to find something called 'boiled bacon,' which is similar in terms of prep and presentation but is pork. But who cares - it's a great Irish-American dish and it's part of St Patrick's Day in the USA! For a high-quality brisket, buy one from a good kosher deli. It will be very salty, so soak it for a good 12 hours, changing the water a few times. It will be worth it. For a variation on the cabbage, you can make colcannon, which is like champ but contains cabbage instead of onions. Shred your cooked cabbage and stir it into creamy mashed potatoes, with lots of butter and maybe some chives. Yummy. Also, turnips and swedes (rutabagas?) would make frequent appearances in Irish dishes like this. And for the reviewers who found it plain... don't forget that what most people know as Irish food is peasant food, and it is based on high quality ingredients and simple prep. Another thing - Ireland is an island! I'm disappointed the Epicurious St Pat's day recipes don't contain more seafood.

Rating: 4
Loved it!! The glaze is definitely what made this above and beyond. Thanks to Saratoga for the recipe (3/4 c. bourbon, 3/4 c. apple juice, 3 T. mustard, 1.5 c. brown sugar). I am saving the left over broth and glaze and am trying to figure out some type of stew to make with it. Any ideas??

