Rating: 3
This is a great example of why I love getting recipes from Epicurious. I'm sure the recipe on its own is very good, but incorporating many of the reviewers' suggestions (start at very bottom & scroll up!) made it OUTSTANDING. I too used my crock pot (set on low) - put in the beef @ 9 a.m. with a bottle of Harps & then water to cover + a few peppercorns & mustard seeds, added the carrots, onion & potatoes @ 5 p.m., the cabbage @ 6:15 pm. and took everything out at 6:30. I sometimes find that the veggies get too mushy if you leave them in all day - this way they were cooked just right. I then put the beef in a 400 degree oven, slathering a 1 to 1 mixture of brown sugar & grainy mustard on top. Let that cook for 20 minutes and it was FANTASTIC - I can't imagine skipping that step. I also made the horseradish sauce, and it was a winner. Made a sandwich the next day for my husband using the sliced corned beef, sauce & raw cabbage leaves - YUM! The only thing I would note is about the corned beef. In MA at least, it comes in 2 varieties - red or "gray", which is New England style. It also comes either "flat cut" or "point cut". A very nice Irish-American woman in the meat section, seeing the perplexed look on my face, told me that I wanted the flat cut gray variety. While the finished version was perfectly salty & delicious, the appearance was a little off-putting. She did note that the red variety was too salty - so that may explain the issue other reviewers had. For appearances only, I may try the red one next time and soak it in water overnight to cut the saltiness. Otherwise - this recipe is a BIG winner. Enjoy!

