Rating: 0
I'm always surprised that most corned beef recipes call for boiling or simmering the meat. I find it is much better to put the corned beef and vegetables, covered with aluminum foil, in a 300 degree oven for a few hours, and then remove the cover in the last 45 minutes of cooking.At that time, increase the teperature to 375 degrees. The meat will be tender but will also have a nice glaze and will be slightly crispy on top.

Rating: 3
This is a very good recipe for Corned Beef and Cabbage, I agree with MaryBeth from San Francisco, beer mixed with the water makes an excellent substitution, and for your non-alcohol drinking friends alcohol-free beer works just fine...my only suggestion on the beer is to cut it to one fourth of the total amount of liquid...and if you really want to simplify your life, toss all the ingredients into that crockpot that has been sitting up on your pantry shelf and let it simmer on the LOW setting for about 10-12 hours...it will come out so tender it will melt in your mouth...this is a great way to do it all in one pot and never have to worry...too often people ruin corned beef by accidentally allowing it to come to a boil and that toughens the meat beyond repair, with the auto temp of a crockpot this never happens.....enjoy!!.....Scott

